<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,261,864]" pageId="9" pageNumber="305">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,585,612]" pageId="9" pageNumber="305">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The new species is distinguished from its congeners by basal teeth of the stridulatory file which are abruptly becoming smaller proximad (
<figureCitation box="[581,664,621,648]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1605,1630]" captionTargetBox="[168,1419,548,1578]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[168,1419,544,1580]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 5. Male stridulatory file under the left tegmen. a: M. niponensis (Haan, 1843); b: M. fallax He, 2019; c: M. crescendo sp. nov.; d: M. himalaya sp. nov.; f: M. tibetensis sp. nov.; f: M. marmorata He; g: M. confracta sp. nov.; h: M. synconfracta sp. nov.; i: Mecopoda_“S” (Sismondo 1990); j: Mecopda sp. from Vietnam; k: M. elongata elongata from India; l: M. minor minor subsp. nov.; m: M. m. yunnana subsp. nov.." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3734494" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3734494/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="305">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[633,664,621,648]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="5.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="305" unit="g" value="5.0">5g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,261,864]" pageId="9" pageNumber="305">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,354,657,684]" pageId="9" pageNumber="305">Bioacoustics.</emphasis>
The song unit is only a simple chirp, made up of a few simple syllables (
<figureCitation box="[1203,1271,657,684]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1942,1967]" captionTargetBox="[320,1265,1175,1912]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[318,1269,1170,1916]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Calling song of the species group confracta. a–e: M. confracta sp. nov., f–j: M. synconfracta sp. nov., k–o: Mecopoda_“S” (Sismondo 1990). Oscillogram of representative song units (a, f, k), a song unit (b, d, l), the syllable groups at the climax of a song unit (c, h, m), and at the end of a song unit (d, i, n). Spectrum of the calling song (e, j, o)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3734488" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3734488/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="305">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
a–d) (see song parameters in Table 3). Its song is very similar to the song 
<typeStatus box="[839,887,694,720]" pageId="9" pageNumber="305">type</typeStatus>
“Chirper“ that was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Nityananda, V. &amp; Balakrishnan, R." pageId="9" pageNumber="305" pagination="223 - 250" refId="ref11986" refString="Nityananda, V. &amp; Balakrishnan, R. (2006) A diversity of songs among morphologically indistinguishable katydids of the genus Mecopoda (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae) from southern India. Bioacoustics, 15, 223 - 250. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 09524622.2006.9753552" type="journal article" year="2006">Nityananda &amp; Balakrishnan (2006)</bibRefCitation>
, but different from the latter by the short interval between neighboring chirps. The relation between duration and period is 1: 
<quantity box="[520,568,765,791]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.08" pageId="9" pageNumber="305" unit="in" value="2.0">2 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName authority="Liu &amp; Heller &amp; Wang &amp; Yang &amp; Wu &amp; Liu &amp; Zhang, 2020" authorityName="Liu &amp; Heller &amp; Wang &amp; Yang &amp; Wu &amp; Liu &amp; Zhang" authorityYear="2020" box="[575,719,766,792]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Mecopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="305" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="confracta" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[575,719,766,792]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="305">M. confracta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[727,790,766,792]" pageId="9" pageNumber="305">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[727,790,766,792]" pageId="9" pageNumber="305" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
compared to 1: 
<quantity box="[959,1008,765,791]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.016" pageId="9" pageNumber="305" unit="in" value="4.0">4 in</quantity>
“Chirper”.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,261,864]" box="[199,1365,801,828]" pageId="9" pageNumber="305">
The species “b1” is widely distributed in southern 
<collectingCountry box="[765,832,801,827]" name="China" pageId="9" pageNumber="305">China</collectingCountry>
(including 
<collectingRegion box="[960,1049,802,828]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="9" pageNumber="305">Yunnan</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[1060,1159,801,827]" country="China" name="Guangxi" pageId="9" pageNumber="305">Guangxi</collectingRegion>
, and 
<collectingRegion box="[1218,1354,801,828]" country="China" name="Guangdong" pageId="9" pageNumber="305">Guangdong</collectingRegion>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1082,837,864]" pageId="9" pageNumber="305" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,261,864]" box="[199,1082,837,864]" pageId="9" pageNumber="305">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,838,864]" pageId="9" pageNumber="305">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name indicates that its song consists of broken chirps.
</paragraph>
